 NotificationCenter } from \"./widgets/NotificationCenter\"\nimport { NotificationToast } from \"./widgets/NotificationToast\"\n\napp.start({\n  instanceName: \"chrysaki-bar\",\n  css: style,\n  main() {\n    app.get_monitors().map((monitor) => {\n      BarLeft(monitor)\n      BarCenter(monitor)\n      BarRight(monitor)\n    })\n    // Single-instance panels (not per-monitor)\n    ServicePanel()\n    NotificationCenter()\n    NotificationToast()\n  },\n})\n","numLines":25,"startLine":1,"totalLines":25}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YCAdZKhpnpv5itk7dqhkLF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me write `NotificationToast.tsx`. I need to implement:\n- Import `app` from `ags/gtk4/app`\n- Import `{ Astal, Gtk }` from `ags/gtk4`\n- Import `AstalNotifd` from `gi://AstalNotifd`\n- Import `GLib` from `gi://GLib`\n- Import `{ notifd }` from `./NotificationCenter`\n- Layer-shell window: TOP|RIGHT anchor, marginTop 48, marginRight 8, namespace \"chrysaki-notification-toast\"\n\n\n- Set up a FIFO queue with a max of 4 visible toasts, auto-dismiss each after 5 seconds using GLib timers, and skip notifications when do-not-disturb is active\n- Create individual toast rows with the app icon, summary, body, and a close button, applying a critical styling class for urgent notifications\n- Connect to the notifd signals for new and resolved notifications, then export the component\n\nWriting component structure... The key challenge is that in AGS/GTK4, we need to manage a stack of toasts dynamically. The window itself would contain a vertical box, and we'd add/remove ToastRow children from it dynamically.\n\nLet me think about the implementation:\n\n1. The toast window is always visible (or shown when there are toasts, hidden when empty)\n2. We maintain a queue of notifications that are pending display\n3. We maintain a list of currently visible toasts (max MAX_VISIBLE=4)\n4. When a notification arrives (if not DND), we enqueue it\n5. We dequeue up to MAX_VISIBLE to show in the window\n6. Each shown toast has a GLib.timeout_add 5000ms that removes it\n\nFor the reactive state management, I'll use a module-level array to track active toasts and update the widget imperatively, similar to how NotificationCenter uses createBinding with its reactive store. The cleanest approach for AGS JSX is to maintain module-level state and let the container box dynamically render the visible toasts.\n\nWriting the implementation now... Writing notification management logic...\n\nI'm realizing this imperative approach has a problem—I need to actually reference the GTK4 widget to update the UI properly.\n\nLooking at how AGS handles dynamic content, I should use reactive bindings instead of trying to manually manipulate widgets. The core issue is that in AGS JSX, the window gets created once, so I need a way to reactively update the toast list and let the rendering follow from that state change. I'll maintain a module-level array of active notifications, bind the window's children to that array, and use GLib timeouts to remove toasts after they expire. I'm settling on using GTK4's imperative `append` and `remove` methods on a box container to manage the toast queue, capturing a reference to the box through the JSX `setup` callback so I can manipulate it directly. Now I'm writing out the implementation with the notification listener and timer logic... Building the toast header... Finishing the removeToast function to handle widget cleanup and queue management, then moving into showToast which checks if we've hit the max visible limit before adding the notification to active IDs and creating its row.\n\nNow I'm setting up the toast row in the widget map, appending it to the box, making sure the notification window is visible, and scheduling it to auto-dismiss after the timeout expires.\n\nSetting up the notification listener to catch incoming notifications and pass them to showToast, unless do-not-disturb is enabled.\n\nHandling the resolved signal to remove toasts from both the display and the queue when notifications are dismissed.\n\nBuilding the notification toast window component...\n\nI'm second-guessing the setup callback API in AGS JSX and how it interfaces with GTK widgets, so let me reconsider the approach for storing the box reference. I'm leaning toward the imperative approach since it handles dynamic toast stacking most naturally, and I need to make sure I'm using the correct GTK4 APIs like `Gtk.Box.append()` rather than the older `add()` method, plus ensuring the timeout callback returns `false` for `GLib.SOURCE_REMOVE`. Writing the implementation... Building the toast row... Still writing component code... Writing the notification toast component...\n\nI'm noticing a potential issue with the signal handlers—when a toast is closed via the button, `removeToast` gets called and removes it from the active map, but then the \"resolved\" signal from notifd fires and tries to delete it again, which should be harmless since the second delete just returns false. The GTK container removal already happened in `removeToast`, so the \"resolved\" handler doesn't need to do it again. But I'm realizing the \"notified\" signal connection at the module level might be firing at unexpected times...\n\nActually, both the module-level handler and the NotificationCenter's handler will connect to the same \"notified\" signal, which is fine since they do different things. The real issue is in the \"resolved\" handler for toasts—when a notification resolves externally (not through the dismiss button), I need to make sure I'm removing it from the container. Let me update that handler to properly clean up both the active display and the pending queue, and handle the case where the dismiss button was already clicked to avoid double-removal.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's a distinction in behavior: clicking the dismiss button on a toast removes the GTK widget but doesn't call `n.dismiss()`, so the notification stays in notifd's list and remains visible in the notification center. That's actually the intended behavior for transient toasts. But if I want the dismiss button to also remove it from the center, I'd need to call `n.dismiss()` when the button is clicked—I should check the spec to see what the expected behavior is.\n\nLooking at the spec, it says clicking dismiss removes the notification from the list, which refers to the notification center list. Standard notification behavior is that clicking the X on a toast dismisses it entirely, so I should call `n.dismiss()` in the dismiss handler. This triggers the \"resolved\" signal, which cleans up both the toast container and the notifd notifications list. But there's a timing issue: if I call `removeToast(n.id)` first to remove the GTK widget, then call `n.dismiss()`, the \"resolved\" handler will try to look up the notification in `active` and find nothing.\n\nThe cleaner approach is to just call `n.dismiss()` and let the \"resolved\" handler do all the cleanup work. This simplifies the flow: dismiss click → `n.dismiss()` → \"resolved\" signal fires → handler removes the toast widget. I'm updating the dismiss button handler to just call `n.dismiss()` and rely on the signal handler for cleanup.\n\nWait, but there's a timing issue here. The auto-dismiss timeout also calls `removeToast`, which removes the widget from the container. If the notification stays in the center panel after the toast disappears, that's the intended behavior—the toast closes but the notification persists. So I actually need two different paths: auto-dismiss should only remove the toast widget without touching notifd, while manual dismiss on the toast should call `n.dismiss()` to fully remove it from notifd and trigger the cleanup. I need to rethink this so the \"resolved\" signal isn't the sole removal trigger. for auto-dismiss - instead `removeToast` handles that directly. And the dismiss button calls `n.dismiss()` which triggers \"resolved\" which calls `removeToast`.\n\nWait, but this double-tap problem again: if dismiss button calls `n.dismiss()` → \"resolved\" fires → \"resolved\" handler calls `removeToast` AND then... but `removeToast` checks `active.get(id)`, if already deleted returns early.\n\nActually, the cleanest implementation is:\n\n1. `removeToast(id)`: removes toast widget from container, removes from `active`, shows next from queue, updates visibility. Does NOT call `n.dismiss()`.\n2. Auto-dismiss timeout: calls `removeToast(id)`.\n3. Manual dismiss button: calls `n.dismiss()` AND `removeToast(id)`.\n4. \"resolved\" signal: calls `removeToast(id)` (handles case where notification is dismissed from center panel while toast is showing).\n\nThe potential double-remove issue is safe because `removeToast` checks if the toast exists before removing it, so subsequent calls are no-ops. But I think the simplest approach is to have the dismiss button only call `removeToast(id)` directly, letting the toast be ephemeral without involving the notification's dismiss method, while auto-dismiss and the \"resolved\" signal also call `removeToast` to handle cases where the center panel removes an active toast.\n\nI'll go with this clean approach. Now I need to write the final implementation, being careful with GTK4 constructor syntax and making sure the Gtk.Box properties work correctly across GJS versions.\n\nFor the labels, I'm setting properties like `wrap` and `ellipsize` directly in the constructor rather than calling methods afterward, which is more reliable in GTK4 GJS.\n\nStill writing component code... a supported prop that gets the underlying widget instance. I'm not entirely certain about this though.\n\nLet me try a different approach—skip the `setup` callback entirely and just use the Gtk imperative API to build the whole toast window, avoiding JSX altogether. That way I don't have to rely on uncertain prop support.\n\nBut wait, looking at how `NotificationToast()` is called in app.ts, the return value gets registered as a window with the app. If I return a JSX element, it handles registration automatically, but if I return a raw Gtk.Window, that might not work the same way.\n\nI think the safest bet is to stick with JSX for the window structure and use `setup` on the container to configure it imperatively—that's the most idiomatic AGS pattern anyway.\n\nActually, I could just recreate the entire window content whenever toasts change, but that's inefficient. The `setup` approach is cleaner.\n\nLet me check what `createBinding` does and whether it could work for custom module-level state instead. In AGS 2, `createBinding` ties to GObject properties, so I'd need a GObject subclass for custom state. Using `setup` callbacks is simpler.\n\nAlright, I'm going to write out the implementation now. Setting up the imports and component structure...\n\nDefining the notification toast system with constants for max visible toasts, timeout duration, and window name, then creating data structures to track the overflow queue and active toast widgets. I'm also adding helper functions to show and hide the notification window, and starting to implement the logic for removing individual toasts...\n\nFinishing the removal function that cleans up the widget and processes the queue, then building the enqueue function that manages the display queue and auto-dismisses toasts after a timeout. I'm creating a ToastRow component that builds the notification UI with app name, summary, body, and a dismiss button, styling it differently for critical notifications. Finally, I'm wiring up the notification daemon to listen for new notifications and resolved events, then exporting the main window component...\n\nStill writing component setup... I'm confident in this approach and ready to implement it. Let me verify the GTK4 API details—the `remove()` and `append()` methods on `Gtk.Box` are correct, and the enum values like `Gtk.Orientation.VERTICAL` and `Gtk.Align.START` should work as expected in the GJS environment.\n\nOne thing I want to confirm: GObject properties like `hexpand` can indeed be set directly in the constructor hash when creating widgets, so that's valid. The import statement matches what NotificationCenter exports, and I'm going with \"resolved\" as the signal name based on the spec. Let me write this out now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"