{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QRKzZExSfYYjNXqjs1QtzW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. I can see from ServiceStatus.tsx that the `$=` prop is used for setup callbacks in AGS JSX (note `$={(self: any) => {...}}`). Also, `GLib.SOURCE_CONTINUE` and `GLib.SOURCE_REMOVE` are valid constants. And the pattern of imperative GTK widget creation with `new Gtk.Box({...})` is NOT used in these files - they use JSX throughout.\n\nWait, looking at the `$=` pattern in ServiceStatus.tsx - `$={(self: any) => {...}}` - this is the \"assign\" prop in Astal JSX that receives the widget instance. \n\nSo the `$` prop in Astal v2 works like React's `ref`, passing a callback that receives the GTK widget instance, which means I should use `$={(self: Gtk.Box) => { container = self }}` instead of looking for a `setup` prop. I can see this pattern already working in ServiceStatus.tsx, so that's what I need to implement.\n\nWhen using `GLib.timeout_add` in the `$=` callback, returning `GLib.SOURCE_CONTINUE` keeps the timeout running, but for my toast auto-dismiss I need `GLib.SOURCE_REMOVE` to stop it after firing once, which is the right approach. I've got the key pieces now: the correct ref syntax, the timeout constants, how to fetch notifications by ID with `notifd.get_notification(id)`, and the proper imports from the AGS library. I'll use the safer approach of searching through the notifications array to find the matching ID, since I'm not entirely certain about the exact API surface. Setting up the event listener to filter out notifications when do-not-disturb is enabled, then finding and enqueueing the notification object.\n\nLooking at the existing code though, the `notified` signal handler doesn't seem to receive any parameters at all, which makes me wonder what the actual signal signature is in AstalNotifd. I need to verify whether the signal passes an ID or if I should be checking the notifications array differently.\n\nAfter checking the AstalNotifd documentation, the `notified` signal does pass the notification ID as a parameter, so I can use that to look up the specific notification object from the notifications array rather than trying to guess which one is newest.\n\nFinding notification by ID... I'm checking the valid signal names in AstalNotifd—`notified` fires when a new notification arrives and `resolved` fires when one is dismissed. For the signal handler typing, I'll keep it simple with `_: unknown` for the self parameter rather than overthinking the exact type. Now I need to figure out how the \"resolved\" signal works in the NotificationCenter component.\n\nThe existing code doesn't connect to \"resolved\" there, but instead relies on `n.dismiss()` triggering a property change event that removes the notification from the binding. For the toast implementation though, I should connect to \"resolved\" so external dismissals get cleaned up properly. Let me write the final implementation now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":14253,"cache_read_input_tokens":61234,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":14253},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2d0aac43-e9c3-48ce-90f3-09f0a6c21830","uuid":"dc243018-0f19-4696-85c3-5d53d30080da"}
